Robot Motion Assignment: Due 11/4/2024

In this assignment, you will extend the dynamic model of the Romi you built in A06 in order to accurately predict the position of the Romi in allocentric coordinates (the world or fixed frame) given inputs to its motors.

Doing this will allow you to give the Romi an "imagination." Built into Romi's software, this will allow Romi to "try out" time histories of inputs to its motors and "imagine" where those might take it. Combined with some optimization that we may get to later in ES302, this could allow the Romi to pick the "best" inputs to its motors in order to go to a certain location or avoid an obstacle.

Goal

Given arbitrary inputs to the Romi's motors as a function of time, predict the Romi's global, allocentric XY position using your dynamic model for Romi forward velocity and Romi yaw rate.

Reading Assignment

To complete this assignment, you will need your class notes, and you should also read the corresponding textbook sections:

  • Section 2.4
  • Section 3.3.2

Deliverables

Start with a Romi robot in Webots. You may set up the world however you like, but you will need to use a Webots world that either contains a supervisor to track Romi position, a GPS sensor on the Romi, or both. A suitable world is the Week05_InClass world in the ES302_Webots repository.

Part 1: Data Collection (10 points)

  • Collect 30 seconds of Romi data in which the Romi moves around in its world. The Romi's controller is up to you (you can use the built-in explorer FSM example) but you should make sure the Romi travels significantly in the forward and yaw directions. Be sure to store the Romi's Motor Commands in either counts or volts, along with its encoder measurements, and its X and Y coordinates in the allocentric frame. You can store these values in separate text files, or in one large text file.
  • Collect a second 30-second dataset, but change the speed of the Romi's motion such that it moves significantly faster. Be sure to store the Romi's Motor Commands in either counts or volts, along with its encoder measurements, and its X and Y coordinates in the allocentric frame. You can store these values in separate text files, or in one large text file.

Part 2: Predict Romi position (10 points)

  • Using the collected motor voltages from your datasets, along with your model for Romi motion from Assignment 6, create a python script that uses the motor commands to produce a predicted time-history of Romi's allocentric (X,Y in the global frame) position.
  • Using the collected encoder data, produce odometry estimates for each dataset by computing forward velocity and yaw rate using the encoders.

Part 3: Compare Webots ground truth measurements to predicted position using encoder measurements and using your dynamic model (10 points)

For each of your two datasets, produce the following plots:

  1. On one plot of X position vs. time, show Webots measured Romi position, the encoder-based odometry predictions, and your dynamic model's odometry positions.
  2. On one plot of Y position vs. time, show Webots measured Romi position, the encoder-based odometry predictions, and your dynamic model's odometry positions.
  3. On one plot of X position vs. Y position, show Webots measured Romi position, the encoder-based odometry predictions, and your dynamic model's odometry positions. Be sure to use axis('equal') to make the aspect ratio of this plot 1:1.
  4. One one plot of Romi Forward Velocity vs. time, compare encoder-based measurements of forward velocity with your model's predictions of forward velocity.
  5. One one plot of Romi Yaw Rate vs. time, compare encoder-based measurements of yaw rate with your model's predictions of yaw rate.

Part 4: Writeup (10 points)

Construct a Google Doc that uses an IEEE-like format (template available here). The document should contain headings:

  1. Experiment Setup
  2. Comparison of linear and angular velocities
  3. Comparison of measured and predicted odometry with ground truth measurements

In section 1, describe your two datasets. What Romi motion did you use? How did you modify it for the second dataset?

In section 2, show and discuss plots 4 and 5. This is your chance to improve your A06 model if necessary. Discuss any discrepancies you see and how you attempted to remedy them. Reference your A06 document if necessary, and provide any updated parameter values or equations that are required (if any).

In section 3, show and discuss plots 1-3. Discuss any discrepancies between predicted (model-based) and measured (encoder-based) odometry. Discuss any discrepancies between those two methods and the 'true' Romi position recorded by Webots. Discuss any changes in model fidelity between the two datasets, and any possible causes for these discrepancies.
